Caution recaptured world markets on Monday as a near 30% drubbing for United States (US) WTI crude oil kicked off a busy week of data and earnings that will drive home the damage being inflicted by global coronavirus lockdowns. Europe’s stock markets made a groggy start, with the pan-regional EUROSTOXX 600 flopping back into the redas London’s FTSE, Germany’s DAX and Paris, Milan and Madrid all fell more than 1%. Damage That damage should become all more clear this week with April global purchasing manager data – seen as some of the most forward-looking economic gauges – being published on Thursday.